Lecture 6. Monte-Carlo Algorithms:¶

General Concepts and Direct Sampling¶

This notebook complements the resepctive lecture notes.

Monte-Carlo Introduction¶

There are two flavors of MC algorithms: Direct Sampling MC and Markov Chain MC.

Let us illustrate both on the simple example of the 'pebble' game - calculating the value of ππ by sampling interior of a circle.

1. Direct-Sampling by Rejection [pebble game]¶

Main feature of the DS MC - memorylessness - new sample is chosen completely independently from the previous one.

In [1]:
using PyPlot

N=100000                             # number of dots/samples

x_in = Float64[]
y_in = Float64[]
x_out = Float64[]
y_out = Float64[]

count = 0

for i in 1:N
    x = rand()
    y = rand()                       # generate samples uniformly dstributed within a square
    if (x-0.5)^2+(y-0.5)^2 < 0.25    # accept if the sample within the sphere
        count = count + 1
        push!(x_in, x)
        push!(y_in, y)
        else                         # reject otherwise
        push!(x_out, x)
        push!(y_out, y)        
    end    
end

scatter(x_in, y_in, s=10)
scatter(x_out, y_out, s=10,alpha = 0.01)

pi = 4*count/N                      # estimation for \pi
Out[1]:
3.1396

2. MCMC [pebble game]¶

MCMC keeps the memory - the next sample is chosen based on the current sample.

In [2]:
using Distributions
using PyPlot

N=100000                                # number of steps/samples
delta = 1                               # parameter related to the step size

x=1.0 # Initial coordinates
y=1.0

count = 0

d = Uniform(-delta,delta)

x_in = Float64[]                        # preparing data for the scatter plot
y_in = Float64[]
x_out = Float64[]
y_out = Float64[]

for i in 1:N
    
    dx = rand(d,1)
    dy = rand(d,1)
    x = x + dx[1]
    y = y + dy[1]
    
                                        # periodic boundary conditions for the walker 
    if x>1
        x = x-2
    end
    if x<-1
        x = x+2
    end   
    if y>1
        y = y-2
    end
    if y<-1
        y = y+2
    end
    
    if x^2 + y^2 < 1
        count = count + 1
        push!(x_in, x)
        push!(y_in, y)
    else
        push!(x_out, x)
        push!(y_out, y)  
    end
end

scatter(x_in, y_in, s=10, )
scatter(x_out, y_out, s=10, alpha=0.01)

pi = 4*count/N
Out[2]:
3.15008

Monte-Carlo Direct Sampling¶

1. Direct Sampling by Mapping¶

The function rand() generates the random variable xx, uniformly distributed at [0,1)[0,1) interval, x∼U([0,1))x∼U([0,1)). Our goal is to utilize random xx to generate random yy distributed exponentially within [0,∞)[0,∞), y∼exp(−y)y∼exp⁡(−y).

One simple way to achive the goal is to relate the two variables (map xx to yy) through explicit formula: exp(−y)=xexp⁡(−y)=x. (Indeed, exp(−y)dy=−dxexp⁡(−y)dy=−dx.)

In [3]:
using PyPlot
N=10000
x = rand(N)
y = -log(x)
PyPlot.plt[:hist](y, bins = 25, range=(0,10), normed=1)
PyPlot.title("Exponential Random Variable")
Out[3]:
PyObject <matplotlib.text.Text object at 0x00000000226DC9B0>

Another example of DS MS by mapping, Box Muller Algotithm, which is a smart way to map two-dimensional random variable distributed uniformly within a box to the two-dimensional Gaussian (normal) random variable:

∫∞−∞dxdy2πe−(x2+y2)/2=∫2π0dφ2π∫∞0rdre−r2/2=∫2π0dφ2π∫∞0dze−z=∫10dθ∫10dψ=1.∫−∞∞dxdy2πe−(x2+y2)/2=∫02πdφ2π∫0∞rdre−r2/2=∫02πdφ2π∫0∞dze−z=∫01dθ∫01dψ=1.

Thus, the deisred mapping is (ψ,θ)→(x,y)(ψ,θ)→(x,y), where x=−2logψ−−−−−−−√cos(2πΘ)x=−2log⁡ψcos⁡(2πΘ) and y=−2logψ−−−−−−−√sin(2πθ)y=−2log⁡ψsin⁡(2πθ).

2. Direct Sampling by Rejection (second time)¶

Let us now show how to get positive Gaussian (normal) random variable from an exponential random variable through rejection.

  • First, one samples from the exponential distribution: x∼ρ0(x)={e−x0x>0,otherwisex∼ρ0(x)={e−xx>0,0otherwise

  • Second, aiming to get a sample from the positive half of Gaussian, x∼ρ0(x)={2/π−−−√exp(−x2/2)0x>0,otherwisex∼ρ0(x)={2/πexp⁡(−x2/2)x>0,0otherwise, one accepts the generated sample with the probability

    p(x)=1M2/π−−−√exp(x−x2/2)p(x)=1M2/πexp⁡(x−x2/2)
    where MM is a constant which should be larger than, max(ρ(x)/ρ0(x))=2/π−−−√e1/2≈1.32max(ρ(x)/ρ0(x))=2/πe1/2≈1.32, to guarantee that p(x)≤1p(x)≤1 for all x>0x>0.

In [12]:
using PyPlot
using Distributions

function rho_0_pdf(x) # initial=exponential distribution
    return exp(-x) 
end

function rho_pdf(x) # desired=Gaussian distribution
    return (2/sqrt(2*pi))*exp(-x^2/2) 
end

rho0 = Exponential() # initial distribution
M = 1.5            # parameter M 
N = 10000
i = 1
reject=0
rand_var = Float64[] # Generated Random Variable

while i<N
    sample = rand(rho0, 1)
    unif = rand()
    if unif[1] < rho_pdf(sample[1])/(rho_0_pdf(sample[1])*M)
        push!(rand_var, sample[1])
        i=i+1
    else
        reject=reject+1
    end   
end

epsilon_values = rand(rho0, N)

PyPlot.plt[:hist](epsilon_values, bins = 100, range=(0,5), normed=1)
PyPlot.plt[:hist](rand_var, bins = 100, range=(0,5), normed=1)
PyPlot.title("Exponential and Gaussian Distributions")

reject=reject/N   # rejection probability
Out[12]:
0.4997

Note that the rejection algorithm has the advantage that it can be applied even when the probability densities are known only upto a multiplicative constant. (We will discuss issues related to this constant, also called in the multivariate case the partition function, a number of times later in the course.)

3. Importance Sampling¶

As we saw MC is useful for computing sums/integrals/expectations. Suppose we want to compute an expectation of a function, f(x)f(x), over the distribution, ρ(x)ρ(x), i.e. ∫dxρ(x)f(x)∫dxρ(x)f(x), in the regime where f(x)f(x) and ρ0(x)ρ0(x) are concentrated around very different xx. In this case overlap of ff and ρ0(x)ρ0(x) is small and as a result a lot of MC samples will be 'wasted'.

Importance Sampling is the method which helps to fix the small-overlap problem. It is based on adjusting the distribution function from ρ(x)ρ(x) to ρ0(x)ρ0(x) and then utilizing the following obvious formula

Eρ[f(x)]=∫dxρ(x)f(x)=∫dxρ0(x)f(x)ρ(x)ρ0(x)=Eρ0[f(x)ρ(x)ρ0(x)]Eρ[f(x)]=∫dxρ(x)f(x)=∫dxρ0(x)f(x)ρ(x)ρ0(x)=Eρ0[f(x)ρ(x)ρ0(x)]

Consider an illustrative DS example, ρ(x)=12π√exp(−x22)ρ(x)=12πexp⁡(−x22) and f(x)=exp(−(x−4)22)f(x)=exp⁡(−(x−4)22), vs IS with the proposal distribution, ρ0(x)=1π√exp(−(x−2)2)ρ0(x)=1πexp⁡(−(x−2)2).

In [56]:
using PyPlot

N=50
x=randn(N)
xp=x/sqrt(2)+2

f=exp(-0.5(x-4).^2)
fp=exp(-0.5(xp-4).^2-0.5xp.^2+(xp-2).^2)/sqrt(2)

x0=linspace(-3,8,100)
f0=exp(-0.5(x0-4).^2)
fp0=exp(-0.5(x0-4).^2-0.5x0.^2+(x0-2).^2)/sqrt(2)
rho=exp(-x0.^2/2)/sqrt(2pi)
rho0=exp(-(x0-2).^2)/sqrt(pi)
plot(x0, f0, color="red", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="--")
plot(x0, rho, color="red", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="-")
plot(x0, fp0, color="green", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="--")
plot(x0, rho0, color="green", linewidth=2.0, linestyle="-")
plot(x,0.1ones(N),"ro")
plot(xp,0.3ones(N),"go")

(sum(f)/N,sum(fp)/N)
Out[56]:
(0.00400554840012989,0.012951112459987979)

We are clearly wasting samples with DS.

Note one big problem with IS. In the real (multi-dimensional) cases we typically do not have a good guess for ρ0(x)ρ0(x). One way of solving this problem is to search for good ρ0(x)ρ0(x) adaptively. A sophisticated adaptive importance sampling package is available at https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pypmc/1.0.
